# Git Multi-Repository Sync Workflow

## ðŸ”§ Initial Setup

**Clone the production repository:**
```bash
git clone git@github.com-scube:scube-org/prod-repo.git
cd prod-repo
```

**Add development repository as upstream:**
```bash
git remote add upstream git@github.com-sabin:your-account/dev-repo.git
```

**Verify remotes are configured correctly:**
```bash
git remote -v
```

---

## ðŸ”„ Regular Sync Workflow

**Step 1: Fetch latest changes from development repo**
```bash
git fetch upstream
```

**Step 2: Switch to main branch and merge changes**
```bash
git checkout main
git merge upstream/main
```

**Step 3: Push changes to production account**
```bash
git push origin main
```

---

## ðŸ“‹ View All Branches

**See all remote branches:**
```bash
git branch -r
```

**See both local and remote branches:**
```bash
git branch -a
```

**Fetch all branches from remote:**
```bash
git fetch --all
```

---

## ðŸŒ¿ Create Local Branches

**Checkout a specific remote branch:**
```bash
git checkout -b develop origin/develop
git checkout -b feature-x origin/feature-x
```

**Create local branches for ALL remote branches:**
```bash
git branch -r | grep -v '\->' | while read remote; do git branch --track "${remote#origin/}" "$remote"; done
```

---

## ðŸ”€ Alternative Setup (Different Fetch/Push URLs)

**Clone from dev repo:**
```bash
git clone git@github.com-sabin:your-account/dev-repo.git
cd dev-repo
```

**Set push URL to production account:**
```bash
git remote set-url --push origin git@github.com-scube:scube-org/prod-repo.git
```

**Verify configuration:**
```bash
git remote -v
```

---

## ðŸ’¡ Tips

- Always fetch from upstream before merging to avoid conflicts
- Review changes before pushing to production
- Keep environment-specific files (Dockerfile, docker-compose.yml) separate in each repo
- Use `git status` frequently to check your current state
```

You can now copy this entire markdown content and paste it into your own `.md` file!
